pageSummary: I am walking from Minehead to Dawlish in 2 days because Of the amazing support they do
pageSummaryWhat: I am walking from Minehead to Dawlish in 2 days
pageSummaryWhy: Of the amazing support they do
story:
We first joined as a team 3 years ago in support of Macmillan when we completed the 3 peaks for Emma 💛 To continue the support in memory of Emma and others who have lost their battle with cancer (George’s Grandma does this year) we have decided it is time to dust off our walling boots and face another challenge!

The team is taking on the 100km challenge from Minehead to Dawlish over two days and have begun our training. We will be grateful for some cheering on and any pennies and pounds that can be spared to this cause.

We will also be taking the moment for everyone living in these strange times with Cancer today - where the NHS is functioning differently and there seems like an added risk. It is becuase of this that charities such as Macmillan need our support more than ever. Good luck team and updates will follow

story:
Hi Everyone! I have decided to take part in the Macmillan Swim It fundraiser this year which involves swimming the length of the Thames from Canary Wharf to Battersea Power Station (in a pool). This totals 11km.

Macmillan are an incredible charity which provide invaluable support, physically, financially and emotionally, to those living with cancer and their families. It is a charity very close to my heart and I’m sure that it will be for a lot of you too. If you’re able, I would be really grateful for any donations! 

I was hoping to complete the challenge in a day or at least in October but due to Coronavirus it’s very hard to get a slot in the pool and I can only get 45 minute slots. I will try my best to complete it in October, but due to restrictions it may spill into November. 

Thank you in advance

pageSummary: I am doing this for future research because we must never give up this fight
pageSummaryWhat: I am doing this for future research
pageSummaryWhy: we must never give up this fight
story:
Hello there!

Cancer has touched us in many ways, whether it be ourselves, friends, family or acquaintances. We all know someone that is fighting a battle against cancer, or those who are unfortunately no longer here with us because of it. We are constantly battling this horrible disease in some form or another, and while we are slowly but surely working towards life saving treatments, we still need to raise funds for this in order to continue vital funding for education, support and medical care.

I, personally, am a healthcare assistant working for the NHS. I see the affects of what cancer has on an individual and those around them on a daily basis. You never think it's something that'll affect you, until it does. 

I am also a part time artist. I may not be in the position to do a sponsored run/walk/skydive/karaoke etc. but I hope to use my art to an advantage, for good... for change!

For every £2 that is donated towards Macmillan, your name will be put in a raffle for a one of a kind pet portrait, hand painted by myself. Any money that is raised beyond the goal, will be sent to a mental health charity - because mental health is just as important as physical health, to support individuals that may experience depression and/or anxiety as a result of cancer. Or if you have the means to, if you please consider donating because you'd like to.

I decided to do this because of a recent close family friends diagnosis. But I also want to do this for the people I have never got to meet, the people that were lost and never forgotten. The people that are fighting this in this very moment.

Thank you for taking the time to read this, lets fight cancer together.
title: Thalia's Pawtrait for Cancer Research

story:
In memory of Pete Louden

On the 9th July 2020 after feeling unwell for a couple of weeks, Pete was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer that had spread to his liver. Sadly he died on 1st October.

Treatment was unfortunately unsuccessful but we received invaluable support from both the Macmillan nurses at St James’s Hospital and Jo, the Macmillan palliative care nurse at home.

The current situation means we can’t have the funeral we’d have wished for so we have set up this page in his memory and to support the amazing work that Macmillan does.

pageSummary: a sponsored walk around Derwentwater Lake because they have supported me through cancer twice
pageSummaryWhat: a sponsored walk around Derwentwater Lake
pageSummaryWhy: they have supported me through cancer twice
story:
Well we did it! 👍

15 miles and 30,000 steps later around Derwentwater Lake for Macmillan Cancer Support. Unbelievable views, beautiful weather, loads of lovely people and banter on the way. 

We had some worry along the way, as we got lost and finally found the car at sunset. However, thanks to the kindness of strangers we found our way and felt very proud to have completed our challenge. 

Not bad for two pensioners! 😉

Thank you all for your encouragement and support.

Why this challenge means so much to us:

From Linda - I want to raise funds for Macmillan Cancer Support because they have supported me through two periods of cancer, including breast cancer and head and neck cancer. Their support meant so much to me and was invaluable. So many of us have friends and family who have lived through the anguish of cancer. 

From Pat - I have sadly lost a few close friends over the years. I really appreciate all the support Macmillan gave to them. 

Your kind donation will go directly to Macmillan. Thank you all so much for your support. 💚💚
title: Linda and Pat's Derwentwater challenge page

pageSummary: Ran a solo marathon because they need funds to continue their great work
pageSummaryWhy: they need funds to continue their great work
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

It's been a crap year. We've lost friends far too soon and not been able to remember them in the way we normally would. But even at this difficult time, Macmillan staff have done a fantastic job supporting their families at their time of need.

Running has helped me stay positive through some hard times, so I decided to run a marathon to celebrate the lives of those we've lost this year and to support the charity who have done such great work to help their families.

Please give whatever you can to fund Macmillan's great work.

Thank you.

story: On 11 March 2015 I tore a calf muscle at our kids group in church. I was being competetive, as usual. However, this accident, a broken wrist and my other calf torn (over the period of a few years) really impacted on my overall fitness and health. During the 2018 October break I got so concerned about my health I started to get some advice. A good friend, Lee Morrison helped me up, and on my way. It was the beginning of a road to recovery. I am pleased to report a great turn around in my health, encouraged also by my son as we got the bikes out and started cycling in the Cairngorms last summer. Now I want to push a bit furhter and raise money for McMillan while pushing on with the cycling.

pageSummary: Cycle The South Downs Way in 4 days because Cycling up the hills raised our heart rates!
pageSummaryWhat: Cycle The South Downs Way in 4 days
pageSummaryWhy: Cycling up the hills raised our heart rates!
story: 25 years ago we cycled the length of The South Downs Way from Eastbourne to Winchester in 4 days. We decided to challenge ourselves to repeat it but in the opposite direction. Starting on 28th September we cycled 101 miles and climbed 11,200 ft (the equivalent of climbing Snowdon 4 times!). We had some glorious weather but also some heavy showers and managed to complete the challenge on 1st October. It certainly got our hearts racing so we decided to donate to The British Heart Foundation. If you would also like to donate it would be much appreciated. Thank you.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge weve faced in our 60 year history. And its led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, weve never needed people like you more.

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into groundbreaking science and support for the people who need us most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the worlds biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we cant drop the ball now.

pageSummary: For Alan, Dad & Grandad we are raising money because his pacemaker let him live life to the full.
pageSummaryWhat: For Alan, Dad & Grandad we are raising money
pageSummaryWhy: his pacemaker let him live life to the full.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Sadly, Alan's heart finally failed him and he died suddenly at home on Friday 25th September, 2020.  Beloved husband of Jacqui since 1998, and previously Janet, Dad to Mark and Susan, Father-in-Law to Saya and Daniel, Grandad to Oliver, Sophia, Archie and Seth, cousin to Edith although more like a brother, and uncle to Edith's family; he will be sadly missed, but well remembered.

Alan was a great outdoors person, always active.  20 Years ago we were cycling on Arran, coming over "The String" road back to Brodick when he first started feeling breathless and from then on he struggled on the hills whilst cycling or walking.  Investigations finally diagnosed an unusual form of Arrythmia, and after many tests and cardiology visits he was eventually fitted (2005) with a new form of pacemaker.  Brand new, cutting edge technology, so new that the consultant fitting it at Ayr hospital had to phone the technical experts in Glasgow for instructions whilst undertaking the procedure.  Alan was chuffed to bits about this and delighted in recounting the story afterwards as he was awake and involved in the discussion.  

Alan's fitness and "athletic heart" had masked the heart condition previously.  A keen cyclist, hill walker and motorbiker we were always out making the most of all weathers.  The circulation problems made him feel the cold more than others which was a great excuse to buy a range of heated clothing the weather never got in the way.  

This pacemaker served him well for 12years, at his annual cardiology checkup he always wanted to know the battery life and the data that it stored, and was fascinated by the technology.  Deteriorating health, especially breathing issues, brought forward the fitting of a replacement pacemaker in October 2017.  The cardiology team in Edinburgh looked after him well with follow up from Forth Valley in Larbert.  Alan always surprised the medical team by his good humour, positive attitude and youthfull looks.  

The medical teams looking after Alan have been marvellous, and the technology has enabled Alan to lead a full and active life to the very end.  We would like to thank them all for their hard work, and to support more research into Heart Health and to find ways of bringing hope and positive outcomes to many more people.

pageSummary: A chance to show off your pampered pooches because it helps fund vital research
pageSummaryWhat: A chance to show off your pampered pooches
story:
Thanks for visiting our page. We're raising money for the British Heart Foundation and we' d be so grateful for your support. 

You can enter your dog into more than one category if you wish - just make sure to let us know which categories you are entering your dog into. When paying entry fee (£5 per category) - please state your name and the name of the dog as well please. Once you have paid your entry fee - please message the BHF Lewis and Harris Group's Facebook page with a clear picture of your dog (or 30 sec video for the clever canines category) along with your name, the dog's name and what category/(ies) you wish to enter into. Only dog owners based in Lewis and Harris will be able to enter but others can donate to BHF to support the cause if they wish.

This event is kindly sponsored by Willowglen Garden Centre in Stornoway. Winners of each category will receive a medal and goody bag of prizes and we will also have a best in show prize and the winner of this will receive a bumper hamper of dog goodies. Items in the hamper also donated by Hebridean Hounds (voucher) , Tesco Stornoway (voucher), Kay Pidcock (custom made Harris Tweed dog collar) and The Old Mill Veterinary practice Stornoway. Full list will be published on our Facebook page.

There will be a public vote on Facebook in the coming weeks to determine a shortlist for each category and then our judging panel of experts will be live on zoom and Facebook on 14th November to announce winners in the grand final!

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help us hit our target. Thanks!

story: Great Ormond Street Hospital supports seriously ill children from all over the UK. Since 2012, Premier Inn and Restaurants have been proud partners of Great Ormond Street Hospital Charity and we know our passionate teams have taken part in many brilliant fundraising events as well as volunteering at national events around the country and at the hospital. During these uncertain times our teams continue to achieve incredible things, challenging themselves to conquer their Everest and take care of their wellbeing. We are looking to continue the fantastic fundraising achieved through our partnership by supporting our teams in their creative and dedicated ways of personal achievement. We are #innthistogether and together, we can continue our incredible work.

A better future for seriously ill children starts here.

pageSummary: I’’m going sober for two months and raising money because cancer needs to be beaten.
pageSummaryWhat: I’’m going sober for two months and raising money
story:
I stopped drinking on 26.08 and my aim was to do one whole month. During that time I decided to challenge myself to go two full months and raise some money along the way. If you can donate anything at all it will go to a great cause helping fund scientists, doctors and nurses to help beat cancer sooner.

Our family has been affected directly by cancer, we have lost loved ones and are so fortunate that our Grandma is a cancer survivor. I want to do what I can to make some impact no matter how small by raising money. We all know someone who has lost a loved one to cancer or have family members fighting cancer now.

Stopping drinking isn’t anything spectacular but if I can raise a little money along the way it would actually mean something. It’s a difficult time for Cancer Research as they are facing more challenges now during this pandemic therefore any money donated is needed now more than ever. Money donated will go into the prevention, diagnosis and treatment of cancer. Our family has been so fortunate to see our Grandma beat cancer and we know how important it is that cancer research continues to get the help they need to continue. Hopefully one day no one will have to suffer from cancer again.

If you are able to donate any amount of money to this cause it would be greatly appreciated. Thanks in advance and thank you for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Cancer affects so many people’s lives and it is such a cruel disease.  Throughout my life, many of my Family and Friends have been diagnosed with a form of Cancer.  Some have survived - some have not.  This life changing Research is vital to help more people beat Cancer’s butt and continue to live their lives.  This is just my way of helping this Charity during these unprecedented and challenging times.

Anyone that knows me well will know that I have never really been able to run (I would say that I still can’t) and I am really trying to improve my lifestyle and this has certainly been a challenge.  I will not only be running a 10K to raise money for Cancer Research (to help promote Breast Cancer Awareness Month), but I will also be running another 2 x 10k’s to commemorate VE Day and for Remembrance Day to thank all those Servicemen and Women that gave so much for us all.  I have ordered Medals that I will award myself when I complete them!!!! This will help encourage me to complete them!

eventName: Very Charity Scenario 5: Two 24-Hour+ Gaming Marathons (and more!)
pageSummary: We're raising money because cancer sucks.
story:
What?

We're staying up for 24 hours or more playing video games, and you can watch us! Unless there's an internet-related disaster, you'll be able to view the event on Twitch.

https://www.twitch.tv/veryscaryscenario 

When?

This is an especially weird year, as our usual eight participants aren't able to meet in the same way due to a certain virus. We'll all be getting in on the streaming action in one way or another though! This year's schedule is as follows:

  • Stream 1 (South): 7th November, from 9am until finish
  • Stream 2 (North): 14th November, from 9am until finish
  • Stream 3 (Midlands): 
  • Stream 4 (Wales): 
  • Stream 5 (Sweden):

But what does 'until finish' mean? For every £250 we raise we'll be adding an extra hour onto these streams, up to a maximum of £1250/5 hours. You have the ability to turn 24-hour marathons into 29-hour marathons!

Who?

Very Scary Scenario is a group of people that like to hang out and play games. We also occasionally get together and make our own, including one about a duck that travels around the UK on Twitter, and that one about vaping. You can find more info on our website, https://vscary.co.

Very South Scenario

  • Chris Walden
  • Jack Walden
  • Nathan Walden

Very North Scenario

  • colons
  • Peter Shillito

Very Midlands Scenario

  • Adam Reeves

Very Wales Scenario

  • Adam Pearson

Very Sweden Scenario

  • Alexander Rennerfelt

Why?

Everyone from Very Scary Scenario has been affected by cancer in some form. We've lost parents, aunts, uncles, grandparents, friends... the list goes on. We want to do what little we can to help fight against cancer.

With your donation we'll be able to help people who can't feasibly stay up for a whole day playing stupid video games on the internet.

We've done charity streams for the past four years, raising over £4000 for various charities. We hope that with your help and a lack of sleep on our part, we'll be able to raise even more money for good causes this year and in the future!

Thank you, 

Very Scary Scenario
title: Very Charity Scenario 5: Two 24-Hour+ Gaming Marathons (and more!)

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
charity.registrationNumber: 207994 (England & Wales) and SC038731 (Scotland)
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last.

We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel.

We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how.

Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK.

And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk.

We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
At the Marie Curie Hospice, Liverpool, we give expert care to people with a terminal illness, and their loved ones every day of the year. Our hospice team includes doctors, nurses, physiotherapists, social workers and many more, and is supported by local people who freely volunteer their time and energy to help us run the hospice.

As well as being a place where people can stay to get the expert care they need in a friendly and homely setting, we also support people visiting with clinics and therapies. These include yoga, exercise classes and relaxation. People using the day unit can also get together over a freshly cooked lunch from our chefs.

Relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night, and stay with their loved ones if they wish to. 

We need to raise £6,397 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. Thank you for helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in in Liverpool, get the care and support they need.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
RNLI Fish Supper is our annual charity and social event of the autumn which supports our lifesaving work. It's been a difficult and uncertain year. Income is falling, yet our lifesavers have been busier than ever. With your kind support, together we can rescue more people in peril at sea. Our staff and volunteers are coming together to celebrate their work and support the lifeboats in the South West.

Lifeboats in the South West protect hundreds of communities through their 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. The stunning coastline of Cornwall, Devon, Dorset, Somerset, Isles of Scilly and the Channel Islands are enjoyed by millions of people from across the country every year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

Thank you for your support.
title: RNLI South West Region - Lifesavers Fund

story:
Jean Gillies, formerly of Tudor Cottage in Reydon (Southwold), passed away peacefully on 28th September, aged 92 years.

Jean was a much loved mother, stepmother, grandma, great grandma and aunt and will be greatly missed by all her family. Drama was her great passion and as a speech and drama teacher for many years, I know she touched the lives of many with her enthusiasm, dedication, understanding and sense of fun. She was an inspiration to all who knew her and was at the heart of every community to which she belonged.

The funeral service is on Tuesday 13th October at 1pm at Test Valley Crematorium. When times are better, hopefully next year, there will also be a memorial service at St Margaret's Church in Reydon.
title: In loving memory of Jean Gillies

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
Hello everyone! Having watched Our Planet, Sir David Attenborough's recent Netflix documentary, it is clear that our relationship with the natural world is - for lack of a better word - broken.

Biodiversity - the rich variety of life on Earth - is being lost at an incredible rate. As highlighted in The Living Planet Report 2020, the world's populations of amphibians, birds, fish, mammals and reptiles have seen an alarming average decline of 68% over the course of the past 50 years.

Time is running out and we must act now if nature is going to recover. That being the case, I will be rowing/erging 68km every week, over the course of the next 50 weekdays, to raise money for the WWF. As such, I would be eternally grateful for your support over the weeks and months ahead and your contributions to a charity that is very close to my heart would be greatly appreciated.

Why the WWF? The WWF is at the center of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. While 2020 has been a terrible year for many reasons, this is an opportunity for us all to work together and build a future in which both humanity and nature can thrive. Needless to say, any donation, however small, would be gratefully received. Thank you.

Best wishes,

Ross

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
eventName: Raising Money for Doctors Without Borders
story:
Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation.

We provide emergency assistance to people affected by armed conflict, epidemics and natural or man-made disasters, without discrimination and irrespective of race, religion, gender or political affiliation. 

We work in over 70 countries and go to the places where others cannot or choose not to go.
